Commercial licensing must reinforce this confidence rather than diminish it.

Guiding Principles

The Commercial Licensing Architecture is governed by the following immutable principles.

Principle 1

Commercial trust must never compromise operational trust.

Principle 2

Customer ownership always supersedes vendor convenience.

Principle 3

Commercial licensing validates entitlement.

Operational security validates trust.

These responsibilities must never be combined.

Principle 4

Every customer deployment remains independently operable.

Commercial licensing must not require continuous communication with vendor-operated infrastructure.

Principle 5

Security architecture must never depend upon commercial architecture.

Historical decisions, governance records, audit history, and organizational knowledge must survive changes to commercial licensing.

Principle 6

Customers own security.

USOP owns software.

These ownership boundaries remain explicit throughout the architecture.

Principle 7

Backend systems enforce commercial entitlement.

Frontend systems present commercial state.

Commercial authorization decisions are never delegated to client-side code.

Principle 8

Commercial architecture must scale with the platform.

Future capabilities should be introduced through modular commercial entitlements rather than redesigning the licensing model.

The Defining Principle

Everything in this specification derives from one architectural statement:

Commercial trust must never compromise operational trust.

This principle governs every future licensing decision within USOP.

Whenever commercial convenience conflicts with customer ownership, operational security, or long-term customer trust, the architecture must favor customer trust.

