Section 8
Canonical Commercial Model

The Commercial Licensing Architecture is composed of seven canonical commercial objects.

Each object has one clearly defined responsibility.

Commercial objects intentionally remain independent of operational security objects such as Identities, Accounts, Groups, Decision Records, Governance Policies, and Provider Connectors.

This separation preserves architectural clarity while preventing commercial concerns from becoming intertwined with operational security.

The canonical commercial objects are:

Organization

↓

Deployment

↓

License

↓

Subscription State

↓

Seat

↓

Entitlement

↓

Commercial Module

Each object represents a distinct architectural responsibility.

No commercial object should duplicate or subsume another.

8.1 Organization

An Organization represents the canonical customer administrative boundary within USOP.

Organizations own:

• Platform Users

• Governance Settings

• Decision Records

• Audit History

• Commercial Entitlements

• Connected Provider Environments

Organizations do not represent:

• Microsoft Entra Tenants

• AWS Accounts

• GitHub Organizations

• Individual Connectors

• Commercial Licenses

• Deployments

An Organization may connect to multiple external provider environments simultaneously.

Organizations remain stable regardless of infrastructure changes, deployment migrations, licensing renewals, or provider reconfiguration.

Organizations are considered permanent administrative boundaries.

8.2 Deployment

A Deployment represents one customer-operated installation of USOP.

Examples include:

• Docker Compose deployment

• Kubernetes deployment

• OpenShift deployment

• Air-gapped deployment

• High Availability deployment

A Deployment is intentionally independent of:

• Hostnames

• Container IDs

• MAC addresses

• CPU serial numbers

• Virtual machine identifiers

• Kubernetes pod identifiers

These infrastructure components may change without altering the Deployment.

Deployments are identified by a stable Deployment Identifier generated and preserved by USOP.

Deployment identifiers should survive:

• Hardware replacement

• Disaster recovery

• Container recreation

• Kubernetes scheduling

• Platform upgrades

The Deployment exists to identify the installed platform—not the underlying infrastructure.

8.3 License

A License is a cryptographically signed commercial entitlement issued by USOP.

A License defines:

• Commercial Edition

• Commercial Purpose

• Organization Binding

• Optional Deployment Binding

• Seat Entitlements

• Feature Entitlements

• Effective Date

• Expiration Date

• Issuance Timestamp

• Signing Key Identifier

• License Format Version

Licenses are immutable.

Any commercial change results in issuance of a new License rather than modification of an existing License.

Licenses never contain:

• Customer secrets

• Provider credentials

• Audit history

• Decision history

• Security evidence

• Vendor private signing keys

8.4 Subscription State

Subscription State is the runtime interpretation of the currently installed License.

Subscription State is derived.

It is never the commercial source of truth.

Subscription State contains:

• Validation Status

• Commercial Status

• Effective Commercial Edition

• Seat Availability

• Active Seat Count

• Enabled Commercial Modules

• Enabled Feature Entitlements

• Validation Timestamp

• Expiration State

• Grace Period State

Subscription State may be recalculated at any time using:

• Organization

• Installed License

• Current Time

• Deployment Information

Subscription State should never require manual modification.

8.5 Seat

A Seat represents one active commercial access allocation assigned to a Platform User.

Seats exist independently from synchronized identities.

A synchronized Microsoft Entra identity does not consume a Seat until access to USOP is granted.

Seats are released when:

• Platform User access is revoked

• Platform User is disabled

• Organization policy permits automatic seat release

Historical attribution remains preserved after seat release.

Seats never affect historical Decision Records or Audit Events.

8.6 Entitlement

An Entitlement represents one commercially licensed capability.

Examples include:

• Threat Intelligence

• Executive Reporting

• Attack Path Analysis

• Compliance

• Future Modules

Entitlements are evaluated exclusively by the backend.

Frontend applications may present entitlement information but never determine entitlement validity.

8.7 Commercial Module

A Commercial Module represents one independently licensable functional capability built upon USOP Core.

USOP Core is always required.

Commercial Modules extend the Core Platform without altering its architectural foundations.

Examples include:

• Threat Intelligence

• Compliance

• CIEM

• CIAM

• PAM

• Executive Reporting

• Workflow Automation

• Future Platform Extensions

Commercial Modules enable independent product evolution while preserving one consistent Core Platform.

PART III
License Lifecycle & Validation Architecture

This section answers:

How does a commercial license become runtime authorization?

Notice...

Not authentication.

Not permissions.

Commercial entitlement.

Section 9
License Lifecycle

Every commercial license progresses through a predictable lifecycle.

The lifecycle establishes commercial entitlement without compromising customer ownership or operational security.

The canonical lifecycle is:

Vendor Creates License
            │
            ▼
Customer Receives License
            │
            ▼
Customer Installs License
            │
            ▼
USOP Validates License
            │
            ▼
Subscription State Derived
            │
            ▼
Seat Enforcement
            │
            ▼
Feature Entitlement Evaluation
            │
            ▼
Platform Operation
            │
            ▼
Renewal or Replacement

Every stage is deterministic.

No stage should require manual modification of commercial runtime state.

9.1 License Issuance

Licenses are issued exclusively by the USOP License Authority.

The License Authority is responsible for:

• Creating canonical license payloads

• Digitally signing licenses

• Assigning license identifiers

• Assigning commercial purpose

• Assigning edition

• Assigning commercial modules

• Assigning commercial entitlements

• Assigning expiration

The private signing key never leaves the License Authority.

9.2 License Distribution

Customers receive licenses through approved commercial channels.

Examples include:

• Customer portal

• Secure download

• Commercial onboarding

• Support-assisted replacement

The distribution mechanism is independent of license validation.

USOP validates licenses locally after installation.

9.3 License Installation

License installation is a customer-controlled administrative operation.

Installation records:

• Installation timestamp

• Installing Platform User

• Organization

• Deployment

• Previous License

• Audit Event

Installation never modifies historical commercial records.

If a previous License exists, it becomes superseded.

9.4 License Validation

Validation confirms:

• Signature integrity

• Format version

• Organization binding

• Deployment binding (when applicable)

• Effective date

• Expiration

• License purpose

• Commercial edition

• Commercial modules

• Feature entitlements

Validation never requires:

• Internet connectivity

• Vendor authentication

• Cloud services

• Customer identity transmission

• Customer security data

Validation is entirely local.

9.5 Runtime Derivation

A successfully validated License produces one Subscription State.

Subscription State represents the operational interpretation of commercial entitlement.

It is recreated whenever:

• USOP starts

• A License changes

• Time-based commercial state changes

• Administrative refresh occurs

Runtime derivation is deterministic.

No user should manually edit Subscription State.

9.6 Renewal

Renewal is the installation of a newly issued License.

Renewal does not require:

• Database migration

• User recreation

• Provider reconfiguration

• Governance recreation

• Decision migration

• Audit modification

Only the active License changes.

Subscription State is recalculated.

9.7 Replacement

Replacement occurs when an existing License must be superseded before expiration.

Examples include:

• Commercial changes

• Administrative correction

• Organization changes

• Deployment replacement

• Disaster recovery

Replacement preserves:

• Historical audit

• Historical licensing events

• Historical commercial attribution

9.8 Expiration

License expiration changes commercial entitlement.

License expiration must never:

Delete Decisions

Delete Audit History

Delete Governance

Delete Platform Users

Delete Organizations

Delete Security Data

Delete Institutional Knowledge

Commercial expiration affects operation—not ownership.

Section 10
Validation Architecture

Validation exists to establish commercial trust.

Validation never establishes operational trust.

Operational trust is established separately through enterprise authentication and backend authorization.

Validation answers one question:

Is this Organization commercially entitled to operate this capability?

Nothing more.

10.1 Trust Chain

The canonical trust chain is:

USOP License Authority

Private Signing Key

↓

Signed License

↓

Customer Installation

↓

Public Key Validation

↓

Validated License

↓

Subscription State

↓

Commercial Entitlements

Operational security is intentionally absent from this chain.

10.2 Offline Validation

Offline validation is a foundational architectural requirement.

Every supported deployment should validate commercial entitlement without requiring continuous Internet connectivity.

Offline validation supports:

• Government

• Defense

• Air-gapped

• Critical Infrastructure

• Restricted Enterprise Networks

Internet connectivity may enhance licensing operations but must never become a prerequisite for platform operation.

10.3 Validation Failures

Validation failures should produce deterministic runtime states.

Examples include:

• Invalid Signature

• Expired License

• Unsupported Format

• Organization Mismatch

• Deployment Mismatch

• Corrupted Payload

• Unknown Signing Key

Validation failures produce:

• Audit Event

• Subscription State Update

• Administrative Visibility

Validation failures never destroy customer information.

10.4 Architect's Review

The Commercial Validation Architecture intentionally separates commercial trust from operational trust.

Customers authenticate through enterprise identity providers.

USOP authorizes operations.

Commercial licensing validates entitlement.

These responsibilities remain independent to preserve customer ownership, support offline operation, and eliminate unnecessary trust in vendor-operated infrastructure.
